      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Internet's Wealth Jolts Rural Towns'' (Nevada City Journal, July 16):</p>
        <p>I was born and raised just south of Nevada City, in Sacramento, Calif., almost 50 years ago, and remember that place, as well as San Francisco and the Santa Clara Valley, before all these newcomers came here to transform it.</p>
        <p>Some of the changes have been for the better. But there is an inescapable sadness when one witnesses the influx of all this new wealth, as a kind of second Gold Rush, and recalls the follies committed 150 years ago during the first Gold Rush, when people came here with no sense of history, only to strike it rich.</p>
        <p>Perhaps the future, though, bodes well, just as theirs did.</p>
        <p>PAUL CROWLEY  Santa Clara, Calif., July 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
